<TITLE> US gives travel alert for Bangladesh polls </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 24 (bdnews24.com) A travel alert issued by the US on Wednesday warned its citizens of the risks of travel to Bangladesh up to Jan 5 2009, urging caution during the period before and after the general election on Dec 29. Just a month after the Mumbai terror attacks in neighbouring India, which left over 170 people dead including six US citizens, the US Department of State warned of reported terrorist threats focused around the Bangladesh polls. The alert, mentioning that the state of emergency was lifted in Bangladesh on Dec 17, after almost two years, warned that, "Large gatherings including those organised for campaigning purposes in the past have erupted in violence." With these developments in mind, the alert said, the US Embassy in Bangladesh advises its citizens travelling to or already in Bangladesh to maintain a high level of vigilance and to take appropriate steps to review their security awareness. "American citizens are urged to avoid the areas of demonstrations if possible and to exercise caution if within the vicinity of any demonstrations. US citizens are advised to monitor media coverage of local events and be aware of their surroundings at all times." The notice says information regarding demonstrations in Bangladesh can be found on the US Embassy Dhaka's web site at http://dhaka.usembassy.gov/. Visitors to Bangladesh should check with the Consular Section of the US Embassy in Dhaka for updated information on the current political situation, it added. "The Government of Bangladesh has stated it may suspend cell phone coverage during this period. Landlines, however, should not be affected. The Embassy will remain open during elections," the notice informs
